b"[![](../../cdshop/cdinfo.jpg)](../../cdshop/index.htm)  \n[Sacred Texts](../../index.htm)  [Hinduism](../index.htm)  [Index](index.htm)\n[Previous](sbe01047.htm)  [Next](sbe01049.htm)\n\n* * *\n\n[Buy this Book at\nAmazon.com](http://www.amazon.com/exec/obidos/ASIN/B002DEMBW6/internetsacredte)\n\n* * *\n\n[![](../../img/tn_hin.jpg)](index.htm)  \n_The Upanishads, Part 1 (SBE01)_ , by Max Muller, [1879], at sacred-texts.com\n\n* * *\n\np. 30\n\n### FOURTEENTH KHA _N_ _D_ A.\n\n1\\. Rising, the sun is the hi\xe1\xb9\x85kara, risen, he is the prastava, at noon he is\nthe udgitha, in the afternoon he is the pratihara, setting, he is the nidhana.\nThat is the B _ri_ hat Saman as interwoven in the sun 1.\n\n2\\. He who thus knows the B _ri_ hat as interwoven in the sun, becomes\nrefulgent 2 and strong, he reaches the full life, he lives long, becomes great\nwith children and cattle, great by fame. His rule is, 'Never complain of the\nheat of the sun.'\n\n* * *\n\n### Footnotes\n\n[30:1](sbe01048.htm#fr_146) The sun is b _ri_ hat. The B _ri_ hat Saman is to\nbe looked upon as the sun, or the B _ri_ hat has \xc3\x82ditya for its deity.\n\n[30:2](sbe01048.htm#fr_147) The same as brahmavar _k_ asin.\n\n* * *\n\n[Next: II, 15](sbe01049.htm)\n\n"